==Trivia==
*In the comics, Jennifer Walters is a lawyer and [[Bruce Banner]]'s cousin who was saved by a blood transfusion by Banner after she was critically injured by Nicholas Trask. She is able to control her transformation and retain her intelligence as She-Hulk and sometimes worked with the [[Avengers]] and the [[Fantastic Four]].
*In the comics, She-Hulk was at one point the daughter in-law of [[J. Jonah Jameson]] due to having married his son {{WPS|John Jameson (character)|John}} until they divorced.
*She-Hulk is the second superhuman character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to have a job as a lawyer, the other being [[Daredevil]].
*She-Hulk is the third character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to break the {{WPS|fourth wall}}, after [[Groot]] and [[Pizza Poppa]].
**Unlike the two, She-Hulk is the first character to break the fourth wall on a normal basis, whereas the previous two only did it once.
**In ''Whose Show is This?'' She-Hulk breaking out of her own series and getting into Assembled to address the creators is a modern reference to how She-Hulk ripped through the comics to address the writers of her story at times.
*[[Nikki Ramos]] referring to "the savage Jen Walters look" is a nod to ''The Savage She-Hulk'' series.
*She-Hulk has a crush on [[Steve Rogers]].<ref>[https://collider.com/she-hulk-attorney-at-law-showrunner-jessica-gao-interview/ 'She-Hulk: Attorney at Law' Showrunner Jessica Gao on the Pilot and Sex Positivity]</ref> She even has his posterior as her phone's lock screen.{{Ref|SHAaL102}}
*She-Hulk is a fan of [[Hanson]].{{Ref|SHAaL107}}
*While transformed into She-Hulk, Jennifer Walters stands at a height of six feet and seven inches.{{Ref|MSCEUE}}

==Behind the Scenes==
*'''She-Hulk''' in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] is the first live-action incarnation of the character.
**She-Hulk was originally intended to star in an unproduced ''She-Hulk'' film written and directed by {{WPS|Larry Cohen}}, which would've seen her be portrayed by {{WPS|Brigitte Nielsen}}, who posed for photos dressed like the character; however, the project never materialized.<ref>[http://jarviscity.com/2018/04/08/brigitte-nielsen-she-hulk/ Brigitte Nielsen's She-Hulk: Superhero Movies That Got Away]</ref>
**She-Hulk was also originally slated to appear in some capacity for ''{{WPS|The Death of the Incredible Hulk}}'', but that was scrapped early on along with the idea to introduce [[Iron Man]].<ref>Comics Scene: No. 9. Starlog Communications International, Inc. October 1989. p. 70.</ref>
*[[Malia Arrayah]] was an on-set reference for the character She-Hulk.
*[[Sarah Irwin]], [[Matt LaBorde]], [[Crystal Hooks]], [[Anna Mercedes Mendez]] and [[Claire Hoogenboom]] were stunt doubles for [[Tatiana Maslany]] in the role of She-Hulk.

